	"conclusion": "For Notion, the career page partially precedes Linkedin: 23% of matched jobs (10/44) appeared on the career page first, with an average lead of 119 days (median: 43 days). An additional 105 jobs (70% of career-page listings) were never indexed by Linkedin at all. This confirms that the career page is the primary source of truth for job postings.",
	"geminiSummary": "An analysis spanning January 1, 2024, to April 1, 2026, reveals that company career pages do, in a significant minority of cases, publish job postings before LinkedIn. Out of 44 jobs matched across both platforms, 10 (23%) appeared first on the company's dedicated career page. For these early postings, the career page offered a substantial lead time, with a median advantage of 43 days. While the average lag stretched to 119 days, largely influenced by extreme outliers such as an \"Account Executive\" role appearing 632 days earlier, this consistent lead underscores a distinct advantage for candidates monitoring company sites directly. Notably, a significant proportion of jobs—105 unique positions—were found exclusively on career pages and never appeared on LinkedIn during the analysis period.\n\nExamining the distribution of these 10 jobs that first appeared on career pages highlights the varied, but often substantial, lead times. While two jobs surfaced just 1-3 days ahead, the majority offered much longer windows of opportunity. Two additional jobs were available 15-30 days earlier, another two between 31-60 days, and one job appeared 61-90 days prior to its LinkedIn appearance. The most pronounced advantage was observed in three jobs (30% of early postings), which were published 90+ days ahead on career pages, demonstrating that early access is often measured in months, not just days.\n\nIt is crucial to acknowledge certain caveats that may influence these findings. The disparity in data collection frequency is significant, with 200 career page snapshots processed compared to only 6 LinkedIn snapshots over the entire analysis period. This infrequent crawling of LinkedIn could potentially limit the precision of identifying LinkedIn's earliest posting dates, possibly understating its actual timeliness or overstating the career page's lead. Therefore, while the evidence strongly suggests career pages often precede LinkedIn, the exact magnitude of this lead, especially for jobs with shorter lags, might be refined with more frequent LinkedIn data captures.\n\nFor job seekers, the practical recommendation is clear: regularly monitoring company career pages directly is a strategic imperative. This approach provides a competitive advantage by enabling access to opportunities weeks or even months before they become visible on LinkedIn, as evidenced by the median 43-day lead time. Furthermore, direct engagement with career pages is the only way to discover the considerable number of roles—105 in this study—that never make it to platforms like LinkedIn at all, thereby broadening the scope of potential employment.",
